text: Say what you will, but I grew up watching MMPR and I'm still excited for this movie. most of the fans from the 90s are around 24-30 years old now. a more mature take was what is needed to appeal to this age group. and it's not like they took ALL the cheesiness out. I've rewatched the series now that I'm older and DEFINITELY feel that changes were needed, though the nostalgia was real strong. Glad they ditched Rita's old costume. it was atrocious, pointy boobs and all (seriously hope she gets a modernized staff tho). Can't wait to see how Goldar and the Putty Patrol look in this. also for those complaining about how these rangers are delinquents; Zordon needs teens with "attitude", not happy-go-lucky kids who never mess up. Wonder if that ginger bully is supposed to be Skull, if so where is Bulk? and glad they finally have actual armor (Ivan Ooze movie aside), now sparks flying off them can actually make sense. and powers when not in morphing form makes sense as the other civilians in the show never take on any of the creatures that attack, and when ambushed (as we should know it always happens) they need the strength to defend themselves. I figure full trailer will drop in December with Star Wars or something and show the Zords, Alpha, and Zordon.

text: This looks like just a super generic superhero film. I mean, people are walking into POWER RANGERS THE MOVIE! If they're going into something like that, why can't they just have Zordon summon them instead of going into the big typical thing of "Oh, they have to find their powers and then figure out how they work in their normal life first and shit".... I don't care if they make it more dramatic or whatever, but having them just happen to stumble onto the morphers just seems dumb when you could just have them be chosen normally and then easily be like "there's 5 devices so someone picked 5 people" instead of having 5 people just HAPPEN to find 5 devices, you know?  I mean, Marvel made a film about a tree, a talking raccoon, not-She-Hulk, a Russian alien, and Chris Prat going to prison and fighting a guy with a magically powered space hammer and it worked! If people know something's an adaptation of a super hero-like world, then they WILL suspend their belief to accept some cheesy things. Why can't Power Rangers do the same and keep the goofier but most well known elements of the plot?

text: I'm definitely interested in seeing this is theaters. I love Power Rangers. Though i am a little concerned about this being a "darker" take on the series. One thing that really bugs me though are the suit designs, particularly the helmets. The helmets are supposed to be stylized so you can see the animal each ranger is associated with. With pink and red, you can definitely see that. But the others.... I don't see anything at all, and I don't understand why they went that way. Whatever they were going for, the helmets are sort of ugly. All they needed was to add a few different aesthetic elements to them. I just don't get it.

text: I really don't know how to feel about this, as a huge PR nerd who grew up on the series.  On the one hand, I actually kinda like the 'misfit heroes' angle they seem to be going for. The goody two shoes type of protagonists they had in early seasons of the show simply aren't believable to today's kids and teenagers.  Conversely, I can't say I'm a fan of the suit or Zord designs, and there's a distinct lack of levity anywhere in the trailer. Even the worst seasons of the show had some silliness to them that's been a key part of Power Rangers and Super Sentai. I'm not sure they'll be able to capture the spirit of the show, unless they're hiding the campy parts to draw in non-fans. Still, it can't be worse than the last two attempts at a Power Rangers film.

text: By definition of it being a re-imagining its going to upset some fans of the original... I wonder if it will stand on its own merits.  There are some interesting character elements being explored here - the 5 rangers clearly have a lot more scope for character development... but in going down a darker more mature path the film is abandoning much of the campy colourfulness that was part of the original show's charm.  I like so far - I don't love - I'm reserving judgement on the plot and script - I despise the redesign of the costumes. I don't expect spandex (that would look ridiculous) but the new suits (particularly the helmets) look awful.

text: Hmmm... so in this incarnation Angel Grove school is for delinquents?  Bit of a switch from the honor students and charitable volunteers they were in the original.     I can still get behind it, so long as the characters redemption arcs are handled well.  While it was delivered in a rather cheesy way, one of the things I liked about the original show was that the hero's were actually good kids, they cared about school, their community, and the rest of the world.  You saw the Rangers doing homework, working with kids, or raising money for charities.  It made them great roll models for young children to look up to.    This movie is clearly aimed at an older demographic, but I hope that they show the Rangers, as people not just super hero's, as being good roll models as well.
author: Passenthru Alaska

text: PROS and CONS  PROS - Increased rating from G to PG, opening up more story opportunities. - The villain at 1:54 looks badass. - Mighty Morphin Power Rangers - If played right, it can leave a cliffhanger ending, and keep Rita alive for 2 movies, and have Zed appear in the 3rd. - The element of mystery, and curiosity is strong.  CONS - Super Powers without morphing? First biggest fuck up! - I can forgive the black Billy as long as the character remains intelligent. But as for Jason; the original Jason is supposed to be ripped. Like football build. Making him a scrawny little pencil drops confidence in a red ranger leader role for the audience. - Do the actors and actresses themselves have any fighting experience irl? Being able to fight without morphing is also part of the magic too. It's one of the reasons why nearly every other power rangers series afterwards sucked. - Jason romancing Kimberly? WTF! It's a middle finger to all the Tommy fans out there.  Poll measures even, so it could go either way.

text: I have to say, I'm actually impressed. I was too young to get into the original Mighty Morphin series much, but I caught a few episodes, and really got in once Lost Galaxy rolled around.   I like the potential here, and the twists they're putting on how it's always worked; in that the Rangers get tougher and stronger both in and out of costume, and they're clearly going to be going through a phase of flying by the seat of their pants without guidance from Alpha and Zordon (is Alpha in this? I'm not sure) in fighting bad guys.   Also, just hearing one line from Blunt's Rita, I already like her as a potentially menacing villain. She's absolutely not Rita Classic, but all Rita classic ever did was throw monsters and goons at the Rangers anyway. Rancik (the major villain form Time Force) established more villain cred in the first episode of his series by busting out of custody and straight up murdering the Red Ranger before the episode was even halfway done, and this Rita looks to be in a similar vein of kicking ass herself, which I'm totally down for.

text: I was born in 1990. Power Rangers were my life for years. Tommy was the reason I grew my hair out. They were all cool then, they're still cool now but you gotta be real with yourself. You're not the same kid you were back in the 90s. You've changed; we all have. So look, this movie may not turn out to be perfection, it may be trying too hard to appeal to people born in the very late 90s and early 2000s...but it's still Power Rangers, now with a modern twist. I like the darker tone. I like the high school popular vs unpopular kid thing going on in the trailer (following the crowd vs being yourself). It's interesting enough for me. At least it's not an all-female cast! No, I'm not a sexist. I'm getting married in 2 weeks with a beautiful woman who makes more money than me and is, admittedly, smarter than me in almost every way. Nothing wrong with that. But when movies try hard to push an agenda, it's just not the way you do it. Wow this comment is all over the place. Lol.

text: What many people are failing to ignore that this captures a particular vibe of the Era; The Original Rangers was taken from Ky≈çry≈´ Sentai Zyuranger, which for its time was a drama series from an entirely different culture, and adapted into an American series which reflected popular american culture at the time with a superhero element. This film is no different, it is a re-imagining of the Power Rangers series for a different era, more reflective of dramatic content reflective of the era. As cheesy as the original was, it tried to be serious for people who are not nearly 30 and beyond to be reflective of their own personal issues, and it continued for over 20 years to do so through various forms (and included Death, Relationships, broken families and other situations)... but never retained the Dramatic element that many Sentai series took on.  This is definitely an exciting film on its own merit, and deserves a place between the transition of "Mighty Morphin' " and "Ky≈çry≈´ Sentai Zyuranger"... it will be good to see what form this film takes with a proper trailer and eventually release. I know we all think it looks like Chronicle... but Landis didn't write or direct this (despite having written an original treatment/script for a film based on Rangers) Dean Israelite from Project Almanac fame directed it... (and lets admit it, despite the flaws it was still a good fun film with a cool ride...).

text: I can see many people around the world still want this movie to be a TEEN movie like Mighty Morphin in the 90s. They probably don't know that this is a Hollywood 21st century action movie. This is the new advernture of Power Rangers and the director already confirmed that he dropped the phrase "Mighty Morphin" out of the movie's name, it is just "Power Rangers", not "Mighty Morphin Power Rangers". Beside, there will be a lot of interesting easter eggs and references about the "Power Rangers" franchise for you. Moreover, this is just the first teaser trailer and it mainly forcus on the life of 5 teenagers before they can get used to their new abilities. Just be patient and wait till more trailers and even tv spots come out and that is the time we will get a whole new look at the movie

text: This is awful. The Mighty Morphin Power Rangers did not have comic book super powers. They were martial arts experts, gymnysts, and a break dancer whose earned and trained abilities were amplified by the suits given to them. And the one that didn't have any motor skills actually spent multiple episodes being taught how to do martial arts by the others. None of them were angsty outcasts hated by the rest of the school. "Teenagers with attitude" in the 90s didn't mean teens who hated life and society. It meant teens who knew what they wanted and worked to accomplish it. If anything, they were the popular kids. They did after-school activities and were team leaders for the other students. These were people for others to strive to be like. Ideals. Not losers with chips on their shoulders and something to prove. I could look past the horrible-looking suits, but now the story itself is destroyed. Nice job.

text: uhh... fvck yes. I'm so down. Listen haters, it's a re-imagining of the original series not a carbon copy. Take off the nostalgia glasses for a 1 fvcking second. MMPR was revolutionary, it was a phenomenon, and it holds a dear place in our hearts, but it was also hot garbage. The acting was terrible, the dialogue was cringe-worthy, the story lines absurd, the villains were a joke (with the exception of Lord Zedd), and it was chock full of plot holes. I knew at 8yrs old that it made no sense that the monster would just sit around for 10 mins while they transformed. I specifically remember, by the 3rd episode, wondering "why does Rita only send one monster, she literally has a monster factory, just send 2000. and why keep attacking Angel Grove, that's where the Power Rangers are? make a bunch of monsters, send them in groups of 5 to cities all over the world, make them all grow and boom! Earth conquered in 3 easy steps." This trailer looks like what mmpr would have been if the cheap bastards in japan or fvcking Saban had actually bothered to spend some money on the show.  That is all.

text: People like me who grew up with Jason, Billy and Kimberley in 1993 are saying that this is ruining their childhood memories. But it's not really just their childhood though given that Super Sentai, upon which this was based, first aired in Japan as far back as 1975. There have been around 25-30 different red rangers on the American show alone and probably more than double if you include the Japanese version. The oldest red ranger is now in his 60s I think. There have been 24 seasons of the US version since it was released and 40 incarnations of the Japanese version. For a show that has spanned 41 years, we can hardly complain that someone has decided to come up with a new idea for it.

text: I'm not terribly fussed about certain things changing, somethings I find in poor taste but I can set aside. Its not like the original series in whatever spotlight you see it in, is going to change. As a fan myself when I saw the first Transformers movie live action I knew it was only a matter of time, and I just wanted to see it. I wanted a version that grew up with the people who enjoyed the original series. Whether a reboot, or a sort of continuation of MMPR.  Understanding the difficulties of show business I expect that not EVERYTHING I want from this is going to happen. I don't expect to see  Angel grove as the peaceful place it was in the series. I don't expect to see characters 100% likeness to the original characters  What I DO expect is the series respects the legacy its based on. I do expect that the characters at least for who they are are similar enough. I do expect a story line improved but not completely changed. I do NOT have my hopes up for seeing Tommy appearing in THIS film, as much as I would love that. They're going to want to develope the original five first so if he did appear in this film it'd be at the end, and that'd just piss everyone off I think, because lets face it Tommy deserves a lot of screen time.  There are some things I really reaaaaallly hope doesn't happen.  Don't go ghostbusters gender swap like Tommy, not because I hate girls or anything but  nostalgia is what's going to sell this for you, don't shit on it for those who're fans of the character by scribbling over it with a made up character to try and sell to women. There's already females in the story you can use for that.  Don't give shit low screen time for the rangers in suit, everyone's going to expect that the suit action gets enough screen time.  and above all remember that fans will be watching this has obviously got at LEAST trilogy potential but if it fails now  my own and the hopes of others who also wished to see this will porbably go down with it. Lion's gate's made some great films and I'm glad the film's getting the attention it deserves, now bring the fans the film they deserve. :)

text: The movie isn't out yet, and i can already pinpoint everything wrong with it just by the teaser.   They totaly missed the point of Power Rangers, the message they're trying to get across is actually the EXACT OPPOSITE of the original show one.  The original show was about getting stronger by yourself, when something bad happenned, they didn't blame anyone for it, instead they grew stronger and managed to deal with it by themselves.  This teaser show the new movie's message "it's not your fault, it's society fault, you don't have to change, you don't need to get stronger, it's others peoples faults so it's not your responsability, you don't have to do anything, do nothing, things will still works out anyway".   It's the exact opposite of what Power rangers stood for, instead of telling peoples to get stronger, they tell them to just wait and take it, instead of telling peoples they can change, they tell them they don't have to, instead of telling peoples to get stronger by themselves, they tell them it's okay to be weak and things will still works out.    I'm not saying the original show was perfect, or even good, especially since it was made to sell toys, but at least the message was good, and somes peoples grew up with it, and learned from it.  This movie isn't out and it's already pure bullshit crapping all over the original show.

Batman" destroyed both of those characters, and this movie will do the same, and fail like those did, though it will probably make a ton of money. What has made the Power Rangers series so special and amazing for over twenty years is its cartoonish, goofy, cheesy style. While it has dealt with some dark themes, it's done it in a very positive way. Even the new costumes look absolutely ridiculous. This is really sad and totally unnecessary. text: For people complaining about this not staying true to source material,let me remind you that a lot a adaptations are don't stick to the source material. The beloved Marvel franchise for example. I am yet to be disappointed by the movies or performances that Disney/Marvel has provided but those are not carbon copies the source material. Look at Tony Stark, the MCUs beloved sarcastic character of comic relief. In the comics he was not as sarcastic as RDJ portrays him on the big screen, he is actually kinda of an arrogant asshole in the comics who had a substance abuse for an arc. But MCU would not market it that, especially when its tied to Disney and they are trying to sell products. What I'm trying to say is that if they made this Power Ranger cheesy it would not be marketable to the cynical generation that grew up watching the original.

text: I'll be 30 when this movie launches in March. I was 8 in 1995 when I saw Power Rangers The Movie in theater and I owned it on VHS (Still do). I watched all of those corny shows. VR Troopers. Big Bad Beetle Borgs. I loved the action. I stopped watching, for some reason, just before the sequel and haven't been back. Never hated it. Never ragged on it for being stupid. Just grew out of it but never lost my love of it. I do see the tone as more serious in this like..there are actual characters and people with issues. I don't see Emo Teens who are just sad and pathetic. This honestly reminds me a lot of the Alternative school I went to. Some criminals, some just not cutting it in standard education. The rejected. Let me tell you, we had our issues but we didn't lose heart or humor. I truly see that in this. Could it still suck? Yes. Absolutely. But even when I was a kid I wanted to see a more serious tone and have been waiting. This trailer has me legitimately hyped for this film. I'll see it in theater. I hope it is good.

I know that everyone is a fan of Power Rangers for different reasons, but I was pretty sure that the most common reason why people love it so much is because it was so silly and over the top. And do all the rangers have to be bullied? Why? Also, where's Zordon and Alpha 5? The rangers just discover their powers and Zords? Why is Rita seductively talking to the rangers at the end of the trailer like that? I'm not going to completely write this movie off. That wouldn't be fair. But I'm just saddened by what I've seen so far.

text: Here's my honest opinion. It's a teaser so I won't judge too harshly, but this doesn't look anything like the Power Rangers. It honestly comes across as one of those "kiddy" franchises that are desperate to justify their existence to a larger audience. So what we get is a generic dark toned trailer with mopey music and dialogue that's trying to hard to be serious. Power Rangers was an incredibly goofy action show aimed at children. It had cheesy moments that worked with its bright and colorful settings. The fights were over the top, and the show is absolutely hilarious to watch as an adult. Now, does this teaser look anything like that? Not really.... Look, I'm not saying that SOME "kiddy" franchises can't appeal to a larger audience, but turning something like Power Rangers into..... This, will probably make it lose what made it enjoyable to watch to begin with. Some products should stay in their respected group they are marketed to ( I mean seriously, remember what happened when Sonic, Superman, Spider-Man, and TMNT and Transformers tried to shift into something they wenrnt? I remember, and it was terrible).
author: Charles Moore

text: Look, as someone who watched Power Rangers as a kid, I have mixed feelings about this. I like the idea of a more grounded Power Rangers story, and I think the suits look pretty cool, but I also wish they'd cut down on the teenage angst and turn up the brightness a little. I'm willing to wait for more trailers and the final product, and I'm excited to see where it goes.  But it's just a movie. There's no point treating it as if your entire life hangs in the balance. If the movie's good, that's great. It's about time someone other than Marvel got a live-action reboot right. If the movie sucks, then you still have years of precious childhood memories, and a pretty good comic book series that's currently out.  But there's no point in attacking everyone else on the internet just because they agree with you. If someone doesn't think it looks like their Power Rangers, that's a perfectly valid opinion. If someone is excited for the film, I'm betting there's not much you can do to change their mind. Stop treating these films like they're something serious. No matter how it does at the box office, and what the Rotten Tomatoes score is like, you will probably not die.

text: Ok, time to set the record straight with the insensible complaints so-called 'fans' are having. It's a teaser which means it TEASES and makes you garner some interest to give the movie a chance. What? Do you want another Batman v Superman trailer that shows EVERYTHING? Like Wonder Woman and Doomsday? Seriously?   Just because a film takes a slightly darker, more suspenseful and mysterious approach doesn't categorize it as 'gritty' or 'edgy'. This isn't The Crow. The team behind this understands that we fans have grown up with Power Rangers and like (some of) us, we've matured, so no reason that a modernized Ranger film shouldn't cater to our older mindset. The premise of the original show was 'teenagers with attitude'. Remember being a kid and hormonal and mischief and harassed by peers? Did you expect this to be some cookie cutter crud? This is possibly the most honest depiction of life as a teenager. If anything, this film, while it does have it's more foreboding tone (Power Rangers IS a sci-fi oriented show, go fig), the humor and lightheartedness is undeniably apparent.  If you know anything about Power Rangers, it was a rip-off (yet respectable Americanized version) of Sentai and in some if not all of those seasons, the heroes have been depicted exhibiting special abilities outside of their morph. Whether it was intentional or not on the writers' & director's part, this seems to be a nod to that part of the Japanese mythos and don't you think it would make sense that after a human is exposed to some intergalactic energies (morphing) that their physiology would be affected. Again, whether this was accidental or not, watch Day of the Dumpster and the episodes proceeding that. First episode the team, pre-morph had great difficulty fighting Putties but in later fights (still pre-morph), they could handle them no sweat.  Quit trying to shove white guilt down our throats. If you want to complain about whitewashing, you wouldn't have watched Power Rangers which totally race changed the ORIGINAL all Japanese Sentai cast.  I'm not saying this movie is going to be perfect. As cool as the suits look in released photos, I still have my reservations about their design--seems to imitate Iron Man too much, but I get it. Power Rangers should look like POWER Rangers and have some cosmic armor to battle monstrous enemies. Overall, I think this is going to do well and as a long time hardcore Ranger fan, I hope it does despite my reservations about certain creative decisions here. If you think you can make a better movie, go for it. I wish you the best as a fellow fan to see what great artistry you accomplish.

text: Omfg I'm soooo excited for this movie!!!   I've been following it since the day it was announced, to the Ranger cast announcements, Elizabeth Banks as Rita Repulsa, Bryan Cranston as Zordon, and just recently Bill Hader is Alpha 5!  First of all... WHAT!?  What a cast for this movie!!!   Each announcement was like "Im worried who it will be..... OMG PERFECT!!!!!!!!!"   And we haven't even seen the full transformations, Alpha, Zordon, the ZORDS, the freaking MEGAZORD.   This is such a teaser, and it's such an incredible teaser, that it gave me goosebumps, and yes, TEARS.  It's everything a re-imagined reboot could be for me.  There is no "MY CHILDHOOD!! :(" here.  I am OPEN and excited for these huge blockbuster movie reboots, and this looks like it's going to be the best yet!!!  I remember thinking about 7 years ago, "There's no way that will ever happen."  But here we stand today, teaser trailer and all......  This movie is seriously going to be epic!  They are trying to start a new Hunger Games/Twilight/Divergent series (nothing will ever compete with Harry Potter....) AND it would be a franchise started from a 23 year old tv show for children..  to sell toys to said children..) and I think they might have just done it.  The response has been phenomenal thus far.  Yes, the Jason/Kimberly kiss is off, but they are definitely stirring the pot for the inevitable Jason/Kimberly/Tommy love triangle story that will happen in the sequel, if not, movie 3 (ala, Twilight/Hunger Games/Divergent.. lol).  I live where it was filmed too.  So in the trailer where they show the Angel Grove town sign, I've sat on that bench beside it....  I could see how they would want this little fishing part of our City, as Angel Grove.  I can't wait until March 24!  It's Morphin Time!

text: I grew up in the 90's with the original Power Rangers tv series. Seeing so many changes being made to the story with this film feels quite disapointing for a long time fan. They changed the characters, fortunately kept their names. They changed the suits, changed their origins stories how they became the Rangers, they changed the color/theme of how the Power Rangers should be filmed. They were always full in sunlight so that are all quite disapointing changes, and of course the villain, yet they failed to give her the right look and making her scary. I always was very scared of Rita Repulsa as a kid, but this new version isnt a scary villain. But it's reboot, and this is exactly what a reboot is. On the other hand is a very good thing that the stories of the Power Rangers keep being alive, and this is how. So I hope this new version of Power Rangers will be popular and gets a fanbase, and if it's a good film i'll be satisfied, but it will always be unfortunate that there are so many changes.

It should have been that Jason was someone who had done like WMA(weapons), Karate, Judo, and Kung fu, and he was into an MA philosophy. And Billy is getting picked on, that's okay. Maybe have kimberly be picked on too(or an abusive father or parent, having girls being mean doesn't mean anything). Then have the adam be someone who could lie to people and start off a bit of a con man or bully but start to be swayed by Jason. And they still get picked by Zordon instead of ripping off 'Chronicle".  "this is when they learn" to be heroes/Rangers/Soldiers. And Zordon wanted good people who weren't already associated with other groups ect and they'd be around 17. And maybe they did something to stand out after already becoming friends like try to help people around where Zordon crashed. Maybe Jason doesn't see himself as a teacher but he's helping them learn, and they ask if he's going to say he doesn't see himself as a leader either(and he has to accept that). I mean Power rangers is that type of show. They just needed to make it believable and have good action.   Maybe this will work in its own way as "the breakfast club" "chronicles". Seems it has X-men, and generic superhero adventure in there too.    The problem isn't a lack of spandex. It's about what they put in and left out. But I guess if you were expecting a take on the original Rangers, this isn't it.

They only have powers here when they're holding onto their power coins. In the series, that was the same way. In the Green with Evil episode, Tommy was able to zap Bulk and Skull with green sparks (in human form) sending them into the dumpster, while holding onto his power coin. Also the power Rangers can transport themselves in human form. The power comes from possession of the power coin - not the costume.

text: "I've killed rangers before!" - Rita Repulsa  People are complaining about the actors playing the rangers, and the looks of the uniforms, but the biggest change, by far, is Rita Repulsa. She totally changed from a comic, funny, wicked witch of west pastiche who would complain all the time to her henchmen and would get headaches everytime her plans were foiled by the rangers, to a cold, dark, nightmarish witch murderer with no qualms about killing anyone who gets in her way. Also, it's a huge jump going from Machiko Soga to Elizabeth Banks, but I believe she can pull a great villain with her acting, even if she's not very faithful to the original comic undertone Power Rangers had.

Honestly it wouldn't take me too much to get me on board though, all I need is giant robots fighting giant monsters with the awesome guitar riff in the background, if that scene looks remotely close the quality of Pacific Rim. text: This movie is going to bomb, I'm sorry to say. THIS IS NOT A SUPERHERO FILM. Do you see a villain? Do you see fighting? Do you see even a superhero? No. This movie is about kids finding objects that give them superpowers. That's it. Then someone will lead them to Zordon and Alpha (the little ninja dude probably) who will tell them the purpose of their powers and at the last minute they'll defeat the villain. It's going to feel forced and fake. There's not even going to be a moment where the rangers say, I don't want to do this, because they're just going to willingly do it without hesitation. There's not enough time in a movie for them to say no because there's all this other drama, bullshit, and high school problems that they wanted to make sure to get in there. The film should have started out with a badass villain, creating a need for the rangers, and then the kids finding the coins just in time and them saying, yeah we can defeat this thing now but we need courage, and then the film building them up until they finally get the courage, but that's not what this story is. There's no need for the rangers, they just randomly become them and THEN the need for them is created when zordon finds them. That's why it's going to feel so fake and that's why this movie is going to bomb.  Here is the first thirty minutes of the film: the rangers will meet in detention, ditch it, and go wandering around that rock formation place were they'll find the coins and discover they have superpowers. That car chase in the trailer? That's just them running from "security" after they use the explosive to get the coins. The second quarter of the film (the next thirty minutes) will be about them discovering their powers and all that they can do with them and getting into trouble and whatnot. Then someone will find out about them and their powers because the coins are missing and these kids now have superpowers and the little ninja dude or someone will find them and lead them to zordon and alpha because how else are the rangers going to find them if not be lead to them? The third quarter will be about finding zordon and alpha and being talked into being superheroes. The last quarter will be them defeating the last minute villain, which will feel forced and fake. That water scene? That's them just discovering more about their powers. Rita on top of Trini? I bet that's just a dream. If Rita wanted to kill the rangers, why wouldn't she just kill trini when she was on top of her? That's why it's a dream sequence, a nightmare given to her by the power of the coin. This movie is going to suck.

text: OK as a huge Power Rangers fan, this doesn't look too bad. Before anyone starts attacking me, let me explain;  1. Yes, this is taking itself more seriously than the show, but the show was cheesy as hell. This isn't Dark Knight level serious. Could've been much more darker.   2. The characters actually seem to have actual attitude. Clears up Zordon's request; the original team were basically idealistic boy scouts. I like that the team are troubled teenagers.   3. They made the suits look cool. As much as I feel nostalgic towards the classic suits, the spandex and helmet look wouldn't work with this tone and the movie suits are starting to look cheesy as well, so the armor look is a nice alternative, considering what they had to work with.   4. Rita is actually intimidating!   5. The cast seem to actually care about the project. Based on the Comic Con panel, they like the franchise, want it to succeed and clearly had fun filming.   That's all I have to say.

text: There's nothing more depressing, than peeking into the original shows 80's, coke-addled creativity, and then watching this gritty trailer. This trailer sets expectations opposite to what a power rangers movie should be.  Power rangers was just fun and creative. It never needed to be more than that.  It's just a sad reminder we live in a world that takes its' entertainment too seriously. I really doubt I'm going to see a T-rex do a tail bounce into a giant green mans face...   Power rangers is the defintion of campy. This trailer doesn't have a drop of camp in it. They should have left the brand alone and made something original. With how far off from the mark this is, its' only possible purpose could be a nostalgia cash grab. Fuck you, Hollywood. I hope you fall in the ocean.

text: REVIEW, NO SPOILERS.  This movie was good at first, it wasn't as cliche as I thought it would be at the start.  I mean, sure, you kinda have your cliche school children 'group', but that's what the original power rangers was like.   Aside from the start - it became almost too predictable, oh, this is about to happen? Well, I know what'll happen next. It was literally like that, it was comedy more than anything. You're also dealing with too much cheesy story line, sure, the actors were okay with this type of movie but the story line was the huge problem.  It was like watching Dora asking you where the most obvious thing is, yeah, it's that painful.   I do believe they aimed this at the wrong audience, felt like for kids, but not for kids(?) I don't know what that's all about, the "Billy" of the group fitted in perfectly, and he was probably my favourite character of them all, because he fit in his role well and he did a good job with it.  I'd give this movie a 4/10 and that's at a stretch, I would've gotten my money back if I could, obviously point of views are a thing w/ opinions, so don't take my word for it, look at other reviews and check out some clips to note your decision down compared to mine.   Thanks.

text: To all them people moaning like little kids bashing on it for it's dark tone and maturity, just do one and appreciate this movie. It reflects what teenagers are going through and is relatable (as it dives into important and relevant topics such LQBTQ characters, nudes being sent around/cyber-bullying, autistic characters etc, and this helps audiences see themselves in these characters and this is just some of the things that make this movie ground-breaking) so audiences can have a deeper connection with the characters and I love the fact that is a character-driven movie and is a teen movie first and a superhero movie second. All them who cry and complain about this movie should fix up because if they want cheesy and campy versions of Power Rangers (which is fine) then they can watch the influx and dozens and dozens of tv shows that have that tone, instead of being greedy and selfish, let new fans come in and enjoy it and embrace the change, and I personally love the fact that the 2017 movie has a mature tone with edginess and pushes boundaries whilst still maintaining the sense of fun but also realism too and it's sad that many people underrate this movie. The cast and crew (and especially the music composer and director) did a great job on the movie and I just sincerely thank them for bringing Power Rangers in for the new generation and trying to attract more mature audiences. Take it from a guy like me, I'm 19 and I basically wrote a whole SA showing support for this movieüòÇand I use to despise the Power Rangers from Tv (I still do). I watched and loved them as a kid but as I got older, the cheesiness and campiness put me off but then the movie came out in 2017 and it was huge surprise to me and I was taken aback and pleasantly shocked that they dived into serious themes, relevant topics and they also gave positive messages but that doesn't mean that fans who enjoy the campiness can't enjoy Power Rangers because as I said before, this movie is for new fans and older audiences, if they want to watch Power Rangers closer to the boring old source material, then they have the 2 Power Rangers movies made in the 1990s and the 12+ tv shows that is has. Ignore the haters, because this movie still got loyal fans and hopefully the cast and crew can keep on rolling with what they're doing so well.
